{"source_key":"sha256-1d9c4047d1264fa94471600951d6dcb4","record_index":317,"record_hash":"sha256:a6cdd47e9ddece2255bd4c7c3e9468f1c48cd698834f7f8e4c7dc4c2f74312f0","timestamp":"2026-05-29T18:09:57.934Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_kind":"file_edit","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: findings-consolidated.md\n+# Consolidated Findings: PR 13995 / 13996 Agent Trail Association\n+\n+## Verdict\n+\n+This is not an Agent Trail display bug.\n+\n+The bad association is produced upstream by `but-agentlog`. More precisely, the\n+raw capture is a faithful snapshot of the shared GitButler workspace, but\n+`but-agentlog` later treats workspace-global state as session-local activity.\n+That happens across storage and read/projection:\n+\n+- capture records all applied workspace branches/reviews and all dirty worktree\n+  files;\n+- storage accumulates observed targets into session-wide `associated-targets`\n+  and indexes old turns under newly observed targets;\n+- read-side verification tries to reject ambient matches, but the\n+  `environment_promotes_worktree_to_target` heuristic accepts a false positive\n+  when another concurrent session's dirty files later appear in a target commit.\n+\n+Agent Trail calls `but_agentlog::projection::project_pr(...)` and renders the\n+sessions it receives. It does not independently infer that PR 13996 should show\n+the PR 13995 session.\n+\n+## Sessions And Targets\n+\n+The two relevant sessions in `[REDACTED:path]`\n+are:\n+\n+| Session | Real work | Turns |\n+| --- | --- | --- |\n+| `[REDACTED:entropy]` | PR 13995, `agent-status-after-default` | 31 |\n+| `sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0` | PR 13996, `unapply-v3-settings-toggle` | 8 |\n+\n+The branch/review targets are:\n+\n+| PR | Branch target | Review target |\n+| --- | --- | --- |\n+| 13995 | `ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default` | `pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995` |\n+| 13996 | `ref:[REDACTED:entropy]` | `pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996` |\n+\n+The PR branches are currently present as remote refs:\n+\n+```text\n+006b68d5d3062bb74301cd409b3c8717480c9262 refs/remotes/origin/agent-status-after-default\n+3c5823860104bb02eee40f4edbd2fa6cbc7309d6 [REDACTED:entropy]\n+```\n+\n+The local `forge_reviews` table no longer has rows for 13995/13996, but the\n+GitMeta agentlog data still has the branch/review target indexes.\n+\n+## Reproduction\n+\n+The bug reproduces directly through `but-agentlog`, without Agent Trail:\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim review \\\n+  'pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995'\n+```\n+\n+Returns one session, the correct 13995 session:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+```\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim review \\\n+  'pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996'\n+```\n+\n+Returns one session, but it is the wrong 13995 session:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+```\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim branch unapply-v3-settings-toggle\n+```\n+\n+Returns both sessions:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns  # wrong for 13996\n[REDACTED:entropy]   8 turns  # correct for 13996\n+```\n+\n+Raw GitMeta index membership is even broader. All four target indexes contain\n+the same 39 members, split across both sessions:\n+\n+| Target index | `c13f` turns | `2aa7` turns |\n+| --- | ---: | ---: |\n+| 13995 branch | 31 | 8 |\n+| 13995 review | 31 | 8 |\n+| 13996 branch | 31 | 8 |\n+| 13996 review | 31 | 8 |\n+\n+So the raw index is polluted for both PRs. The reader then filters the pollution\n+asymmetrically: PR 13995 happens to look correct, while PR 13996 does not.\n+\n+## Agent Trail Boundary\n+\n+Agent Trail's relevant boundary is thin:\n+\n+- `[REDACTED:path]`\n+- `project_pr_trail_blocking(...)` builds a `ProjectionRequest`.\n+- It calls `projection::project_pr(&repo_path, &request)`.\n+- `flatten_sessions(...)` preserves the returned sessions and turns.\n+\n+`but-agentlog`'s `project_pr` does the real lookup:\n+\n+- `crates/but-agentlog/src/projection.rs`\n+- It builds a review target and branch target from the PR facts.\n+- It calls `find_related_sessions_limited(...)` for both targets.\n+- It merges those candidate sessions and assigns evidence tiers.\n+\n+For PR 13996, the review lookup already returns the wrong `c13f` session and\n+the branch lookup returns both sessions. Agent Trail is displaying that output,\n+not inventing it.\n+\n+## Exact False-Positive Path\n+\n+The decisive false positive is in the 13995 session, `c13f`.\n+\n+At turn 28, captured at `2026-05-29T16:28:09.376Z`, the session still observed\n+only PR 13995:\n+\n+```text\n+branches:\n+  ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\n+\n+reviews:\n+  pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\n+\n+worktree:\n+  apps/desktop/src/components/settings/ExperimentalSettings.svelte\n+  crates/but-settings/src/api.rs\n+```\n+\n+Those worktree files are not 13995 work. They are the Unapply v3 files from the\n+other concurrent session. They appeared in this session because the worktree\n+snapshot is workspace-global.\n+\n+At turn 29, captured at `2026-05-29T16:35:30.691Z`, the same session observed\n+both PR branches/reviews and a clean worktree. The environment now included the\n+Unapply branch with commit `[REDACTED:entropy]`.\n+\n+That commit contains exactly the two previous dirty paths:\n+\n+```text\n+apps/desktop/src/components/settings/ExperimentalSettings.svelte\n+crates/but-settings/src/api.rs\n+```\n+\n+Their path fingerprints match the commit's stored `file_hashes`:\n+\n+```text\n+15927743ca562cdb14b991ec34a44932  apps/desktop/src/components/settings/ExperimentalSettings.svelte\n+448fb348cf62b7226165a0030217b87e  crates/but-settings/src/api.rs\n+```\n+\n+That satisfies `environment_promotes_worktree_to_target(previous, current,\n+review#13996)`, so `session_has_target_activity(c13f, review#13996)` returns\n+true.\n+\n+The attribution is wrong. The dirty files did promote into the Unapply branch,\n+but they were not this session's dirty files.\n+\n+## Why The Bug Is Asymmetric\n+\n+The reverse pollution exists in the raw index too: the 13996 session is indexed\n+under 13995. But the reader rejects it because the 13996 session's dirty files\n+do not later appear in a new 13995 commit.\n+\n+For PR 13996, the timing is worse:\n+\n+- `2aa7` genuinely creates the Unapply branch at turn 3 with commit\n+  `3e25ea72c1`.\n+- Review target `#13996` appears later, after the branch has already been\n+  created and the worktree is clean.\n+- So the real 13996 session only gets branch-tier evidence.\n+- Meanwhile `c13f` sees the same dirty files in turn 28 and sees the later\n+  Unapply branch/review state in turn 29, so it incorrectly gets review-tier\n+  evidence.\n+\n+That is why PR 13996 shows both sessions and why the wrong one sorts ahead of\n+the correct one.\n+\n+## Code Mechanics\n+\n+The capture side is workspace-scoped:\n+\n+- `crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs`\n+- `capture_environment(...)` combines `worktree_paths(...)` and\n+  `workspace_snapshot(...)`.\n+- `workspace_snapshot_with_meta(...)` walks every stack segment from\n+  `but_workspace::head_info(...)` and pushes every branch/review/change into\n+  `observed_targets`.\n+\n+The write side widens target associations:\n+\n+- `crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/write.rs`\n+- `TargetAssociations::add_observed_targets(...)` unions observed targets into\n+  session-level `associated-targets`.\n+- `index_hits_for_turns(...)` indexes previous plus current turns under every\n+  associated target.\n+- Enrichment indexes all turns under every associated target.\n+\n+The read side is where the false positive survives:\n+\n+- `crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/read.rs`\n+- `turn_detail_observes_target(...)` accepts either turn-level observed targets\n+  or session-level associated targets, then asks\n+  `session_has_target_activity(...)`.\n+- `session_has_target_activity(...)` accepts target activity when\n+  `environment_promotes_worktree_to_target(...)` finds dirty files from one turn\n+  in a new commit on the queried target.\n+- That heuristic assumes the previous dirty files belong to the same session.\n+  In this concurrent shared-worktree case, that premise is false.\n+\n+## Classification\n+\n+The clean classification is:\n+\n+```text\n+but-agentlog association-model bug, exposed by Agent Trail projection.\n+```\n+\n+In narrower terms:\n+\n+- capture is not lying; it records the shared workspace;\n+- storage makes the data too broad by turning ambient observations into\n+  session-wide associations and indexes;\n+- read/projection fails to recover because the worktree-to-commit promotion rule\n+  has no session-local ownership check;\n+- Agent Trail should not patch around this downstream.\n+\n+## Pragmatic Fix Plan\n+\n+Fix this in `but-agentlog`, not Agent Trail.\n+\n+1. Add one focused regression test in `crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/tests.rs`.\n+   Model two sessions, two branches, and two PR review targets in one shared\n+   workspace. Session A should observe session B's dirty file in the global\n+   worktree, then later observe B's branch/review after B commits. Assert that\n+   querying B's review/branch does not return session A, and querying A does not\n+   return session B.\n+\n+2. Keep the raw target index broad for now. Changing write/index semantics risks\n+   migrations and surprising older data. The verifier is already the intended\n+   place to distinguish ambient visibility from real activity; tighten that\n+   boundary first.\n+\n+3. Make worktree-to-commit promotion require session-local evidence in ambiguous\n+   workspace states. The practical signal already exists in transcript records:\n+   `tool_kind == file_edit` plus patch/tool input paths. If a promotion relies\n+   on dirty path `P`, require the same session to have touched `P` before the\n+   promotion boundary when multiple branches/reviews are visible or the target\n+   appeared ambiently. Keep the current cheap promotion path for simple\n+   single-branch cases.\n+\n+4. Do not parse arbitrary shell output or invent a large provenance model in the\n+   first fix. File-edit tool paths are small, already classified, and enough to\n+   fix this concrete class. If a session only edits through opaque shell\n+   commands in a multi-branch workspace, it is better to produce weaker/no\n+   evidence than to confidently attach the wrong session.\n+\n+5. Separately, promote branch-proven activity to the review target once the\n+   review becomes known for the same branch. This fixes the legitimate 13996\n+   session being branch-only because the PR was opened after the initial commit.\n+   It should be a small read-side rule: review target activity can be satisfied\n+   by earlier strong branch activity for that review's branch.\n+\n+6. Leave Agent Trail alone except, optionally, to render future projection\n+   diagnostics if `but-agentlog` exposes them. A downstream filter based on file\n+   overlap or session text would duplicate upstream interpretation and still be\n+   brittle.\n+\n+One tempting idea is to lean entirely on GitButler hunk assignments. They may be\n+useful as an extra signal, but they are not sufficient by themselves: stack\n+assignment says which branch a dirty file is assigned to, not which agent session\n+created or owned that dirty file. The missing premise here is session-local\n+ownership.\n+\n+## Validation Performed\n+\n+- Read and compared:\n+  - `codex-findings-agentlog.md`\n+  - `codex-findings-agent-trail.md`\n+  - `claude-findings-agent-trail.md`\n+- Queried `[REDACTED:path]` for the four target\n+  indexes and session-level `associated-targets`.\n+- Reproduced the bad association with `but --json agentlog skim review/branch`.\n+- Inspected the relevant `but-agentlog` capture, write, read, and projection\n+  code.\n+- Inspected Agent Trail's projection boundary in\n+  `[REDACTED:path]`.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-29T18:09:57.934Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}